XML_CASESUMMARY.SUMMARY:
This single event, two-vehicle crash occurred at the intersection of two five-lane, two-way, divided busy urban roadways. The intersection is controlled with traffic lights with left turn arrows in all four directions. The roadway is straight and level. This crash occurred on a clear sunny weekday in the early evening hours with no adverse atmospheric conditions.
Vehicle one, a 1993 Pontiac Grand Prix was eastbound in the third lane (left turn only lane). Vehicle two, a 2004 Chevy Silverado Pickup was westbound in the second lane. Vehicle one turned left at the intersection and the front of vehicle one impacted the front of vehicle two. Both vehicles came to rest in the intersection. Both vehicles were towed due to damage.
The driver of vehicle one, an eighteen-year-old female was heading home from a social visit at a friend's house, a few blocks from the scene. This driver had just started driving. This driver was taking Imitrex, Ibuprofen and birth control medications. She stated she drives this road a few times per month and this vehicle on a daily basis. A partial interview was conducted and the driver would not answer the question about cell phone use. Both witnesses and the driver of vehicle two remarked that the driver was in a conversation immediately following the crash.
The driver of vehicle two, thirty-eight year old was heading home after dinner. This driver had just started this trip. This driver was not taking any medications. The driver lives mile east of the intersection and drives the road daily.
The critical Pre-crash event coded to vehicle one was coded: this vehicle traveling, turning left at intersection. The critical reason for the critical pre-crash event was attributed to vehicle one and was coded as a driver related factor: inattention (i.e. daydreaming). The driver was focused on her conversation on the cell phone and not paying attention to the driving task.
The critical pre-crash event for vehicle two was coded: other vehicle encroachment: from opposite direction over left lane line. The critical reason for the critical pre-crash event was not coded tot his vehicle.
